{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating patch module implications**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the patch module adds or overrides classes, and I'm thinking it might be shadowing something. I wonder if this implementation requires us to run the old FactoryFinder and SecuritySupport when we patch all javax/xml/parsers. It seems like using DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance would trigger that too, which adds complexity. I need to double-check how this interaction works to ensure everything functions as expected. It’s definitely a bit tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class extensions**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how the class extends a patched class from java.xml at runtime. To handle this, I need a native resource or reflection configuration for the service provider and resource. This approach helps me avoid direct reflection. The class name SecuritySupportTest should still be relevant. I also need to consider keeping tests out of library packages while allowing the test package. It looks like I might need a custom SecurityManager for testing, but I should verify if GraalVM's native image supports that. Time to search the repo!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Oxl7W5rGVJZQXIylMUtf6HTk|fc_0daefcc6e951c0ee0169f14aa559f88193a7e84cd3d81faef9", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"SecurityManager|setSecurityManager|java.security.manager\" tests/src -n | head -80", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1162, "output": 2430, "cacheRead": 47616, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 51208, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777420927855, "responseId": "resp_0daefcc6e951c0ee0169f14a80705881939d87ea60a42fc391"}}
